        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>43 Claremont Road, | Alexandra Park, | Manchester,</placeName>
                    <date>Oct. 22. 1881.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have just received the copy of your most interesting volume which you have so kindly sent me.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The subject is new and important</p>
<p>Please to accept my best thanks for the gift. You will be glad to learn that I am much improved in health of late. Sleep has completely returned. I am at present on my way to winter in some warm and sheltered place in the South of England, where I can live cheaply<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I am | Yours sincerely— | James Croll <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Charles Darwin | LLD., FRS. &amp;c—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Croll’s name is on CD’s presentation list for <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2241.xml"><hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi></ref> (see Appendix IV).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">For more on Croll’s health, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13214F.xml">letter from Archibald Geikie, 22 June 1881</ref> and n. 1.</note>
        </div>
    
